ocieties all over the world. The question of dealing with migrants and asylum seekers has dominated political discourse. It has given rise to national and international legislation on emigration and immigration, some of them including discriminatory provisions, pressed laws against immigration (Acts of exclusion) and prompted anti-migration rhetoric and hate speech against migrants. Important efforts have been made in both common law and civil law jurisdictions to protect migrants' fundamental rights to dignity and equality.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigration lawxSocial aspects. 4aForensische Linguistik. 4aMigration. 4aSprache und Recht. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aForensic Linguistics, Law, Legal Translation and Interpreting, Migration.1 aBaider, Fabienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonsignore, Dyango, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoval Pais, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoval Pais, Antonio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuillén-Nieto, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuillén-Nieto, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHartwell, Laura M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Rachel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavissière, Mary C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuzaitė, Jūratė, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmid, Monika S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStein, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4http